In Java, the '==' operator is used to compare the references of two objects to check if they point to the same memory location. When comparing strings with '==', you're actually checking if both variables hold the same reference to the same String object in memory.

However, when you want to compare the values or contents of two strings, you should use the `.equals()` method instead. The `.equals()` method compares the values of two strings character by character for equality.

Here are some guidelines on when to use '==' and `.equals()`:

1. Use '==' when comparing string literals or constants:
   ```java
   String str1 = "Hello";
   String str2 = "Hello";
   if (str1 == str2) { // true, since both are the same string literal
      // ...
   }
   ```

2. Use `.equals()` when comparing strings that are not literals or constants:
   ```java
   String str1 = new String("Hello");
   String str2 = new String("Hello");
   if (str1.equals(str2)) { // true, since both strings have the same value
      // ...
   }
   ```

3. Use `.equals()` when comparing strings that may be null:
   ```java
   String str1 = null;
   String str2 = "Hello";
   if (str1 == str2) { // false and compiles with a NullPointerException
      // ...
   }
   if (str1 == null || str2.equals("Hello")) { // correct way to check for null and equality
      // ...
   }
   ```

In summary, use '==' for reference equality comparison and `.equals()` for value equality comparison when working with strings in Java.

